👉 Constructor Overloading 

Constructor Overloading means having multiple constructors in the same class with:

Different number of parameters OR Different types of parameters
It is used to initialize objects in different ways

Constructor name = class name
No return type (not even void)
Can have multiple constructors
Compiler decides which constructor to call (compile-time polymorphism)

Code :

class emp{
    private int id;
    private String name;
    public emp(){
        id = 34;
        name = "Harsh";
    }
    public emp(int num , String nam){
        id = num;
        name = nam;
    }
    public void get(){
        System.out.println("Id setted is : "+id+" Name is : "+name);
    }
}
public class constructors{
    public static void main(String[] args){
        emp e = new emp();                    // calls default
        emp e2 = new emp(45,"Prince");        // calls 2 parameters
        e.get();
        e2.get();
    }
}

👉 Why use Constructor Overloading?

Flexibility in object creation
Cleaner code
Avoids multiple setter calls

👉 Note :

1. Constructors can take parameters without being overloaded
2. There can be more than two overloaded constructors


